04148nam a22004935i 9781552385074DE-B159720240306010644.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20092009xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97815523850747 a10.1515/97815523850742doi  a(DE-B1597)664069  a(OCoLC)1414456470  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 7aART0150402bisacsh1 aSimmins, Geoffrey, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aSpirit Matters :bRon (Gyo-zo) Spickett, Artist, Poet, Priest /cGeoffrey Simmins. 1aCalgary, Alberta : bUniversity of Calgary Press, c[2009] 4c©2009  a1 online resource (224 p.) :b44 b/w illustrations, 31 colour plates  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aArt in Profile: Canadian Art and Architecture ;v600tFront Matter -- tTable of Contents -- tList of Illustrations -- tList of Colour Plates -- tAcknowledgments -- tAchieving the Modern -- tPortrait of the Artist as Family Man -- tPortrait of the Artist as Artist -- tPortrait of the Artist as Buddhist Lay-Priest and Poet -- tPortrait of the Artist as Teacher -- tRon Spickett: Reminiscences of Marion Nicoll (1909–1985) and of the Calgary Art Scene During the 1940s and 1950s -- tChronology -- tSelected Exhibition Record -- tSelected Bibliography -- tNotes -- tColour Plates -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aRonald Spickett (1926- ) is a Calgary-based artist, poet, and Zen Buddhist lay priest. During his long career, he also taught studio art, both at the Alberta College of Art and Design and at the University of Calgary. Today, Ronald Spickett, also known by his Buddhist name of Gyo-Zo, is best known for a series of ambitious paintings he executed during the 1960s, paintings with Western themes such as posses and riders. However, the scope of Spickett's work proved to be much more diverse and includes genre paintings, landscapes, non-representational paintings, sculptures, and paintings with religious and spiritual themes. The artist's work, as Simmins' study shows, is not easily pigeon-holed; Spickett is more than a Western artist, more than a Buddhist artist, more than simply the sum of his paintings. Rather, Simmins argues, he is an "ideas-based" artist whose work reveals complexities and undercurrents that link him with the prevailing artistic currents of his times, yet also testify to his originality and unique style. Simmins was granted complete access to the artist's personal and professional papers and interviewed him on numerous occasions. Thus the artist's own statements on his life and work make an invaluable contribution to Spirit Matters: Ron (Gyo-zo) Spickett, Artist, Poet, Priest, and are considered alongside critical writings, broader studies in Canadian art history, and still larger currents in Canadian artistic and intellectual life.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aART / Canadian.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781552385074?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781552385074423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781552385074/original  a978-3-11-127416-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010b2010  a978-3-11-127724-0  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010b2010  aGBV-deGruyter-alles